  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Assistance- Country-Level Funding- IOM 2020</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">IOM is contributing to the overall objective of the WHO&apos;s COVID-19 Global Strategic Preparedness and Response Plan (SRP) to halt further transmission of COVID-19, and mitigate the impact of the outbreak, including the social impact. IOM has also launched its own COVID-19 Appeal on the 20 March to guide and coordinate IOM global response with government, partners and donors, itself a component of the UN Global Humanitarian Response Plan. Cox&apos;s Bazar District continues to host more than 855,000 Rohingya refugees in camps with a total area of approximately 24 square kilometers. The high population density, in combination with an already uncertain health profile, puts these populations at a heightened risk of community transmission and threatens to overwhelm the already overburdened local medical system and infrastructure in a very short period. In order to properly address the health and socioeconomic issues caused by COVID-19, humanitarian access to the camp is critical to the well-being of affected populations and the success of humanitarian interventions. The proposed project has two main elements; IOM&apos;s Cox&apos;s Bazar COVID-19 Response and site maintenance engineering.</narrative>
  </description>
